   Stuart Schwartz Date: 11/10/95 
   
   From: KSKD05A John Hoffler Time: 8:31PM ET
   
   >>The second scenario is that Win95 matures into a NT light 
   
   product while NT remains the choice for networked 
   
   environments needed the extra security of file permissions, 
   
   etc.<< 
   
   This is the more likely scenario, and the one M$ finally 
   
   admits they're going to follow. Now the problem remains 
   
   that M$'s solution requires different operating systems with
   
   different APIs on the client and the server. OS/2 runs the 
   
   same API on both client and server, putting it a major step 
   
   closer to the next computing paradigm -- true distributed 
   
   computing. In the well-connected future (which is sooner 
   
   than you may think), when everyone has ISDN connectivity to 
   
   the Internet, people will expect their PCs to run several 
   
   background tasks continuously without interfering with their
   
   word processors and spreadsheets. 
   
   E-mail and Phone-mail processes will have to run 
   
   continuously. Search engines will continuously scan select 
   
   Internet sites for late-breaking news stories. A pager 
   
   system will filter incoming e-mail and phone-mail for 
   
   keywords and page you if your criteria are met. A FTP 
   
   process will automatically download bug fixes for all your 
   
   software whenever it finds new files at designated FTP 
   
   sites. And of course none of this can interfere with 
   
   Quicken or your Tuesday-night 4-way DOOM session. 
   
   Unfortunately, Win95 doesn't make a very good server 
   
   platform. It's dependence on the 16-bit DOS and Windows 3.x
   
   kernels limit it's scalability, portability, and 
   
   performance. For example, Win95's peer networking is 40% 
   
   slower than both Warp Connect and NT (Warp Connect is 2% 
   
   faster than NT). M$'s refusal to implement any standard 
   
   they didn't create, like DCE, CORBA, and DMI, will soon come
   
   back to haunt them. All of these standards are already 
   
   implemented by the rest of the industry, especially Unix 
   
   vendors, and are thus Ready-for-Internet use. 
   
   DCE, which provides distributed file services, remote 
   
   procedure calls, distributed security, and other network 
   
   services, is implemented on all platforms from OS/2, through
   
   Unix, up through the mainframe. The proprietary security 
   
   scheme in Win95 and NT will lock them out from transparent 
   
   access to information on other platforms. 
   
   IBM and Tandem both implement DSOM on their mainframe 
   
   systems. Every major Unix vendor has a CORBA-compliant 
   
   object model that can interoperate with DSOM. Once again, 
   
   M$'s refusal to support this standard locks them out from 
   
   information access. 
   
   All the nerdly shortcomings that make M$ operating systems 
   
   poor network citizens will soon be generally recognized as 
   
   liabilities in the Internet-centric tomorrow. 
   
   John 
