   Here's my latest experiment. I'm going to save some time by 
   
   just giving the overall results instead of exact figures. I 
   
   wanted to test the ability of the different OS's with 
   
   regards to multi-tasking. This is the basic scenario. I 
   
   opened Word, and some other apps and had Word run a Wizard, 
   
   like create a calendar, had a database app re-indexing 
   
   itself, another database app running a performance test, 
   
   click to sign on to (Service) and start a large directory 
   
   (35MB) being copied. Unlike what I've heard about Warp, 
   
   Win95 was the fastest followed by NT and Warp wasn't much 
   
   slower. Now lets look at running apps in separate memory 
   
   space so that they are protected from each other, i.e. when 
   
   one crashes, theoretically the others are unaffected. In 
   
   the real world this protection is a definite plus but not 
   
   bullet proof. OK, now I try the same experiment but with 
   
   the separate memory spaces that affords the most protection 
   
   which is something that Warp always had over the old 
   
   Windows and still does when running 16bit apps. Win95 
   
   currently runs all the new 32bit apps in protected mode but 
   
   the older 16 bit apps it is not able to do so. Furthermore 
   
   a bad 16 bit app can bring down the whole system as some 
   
   shared parts of Win95 are 16 bit. So for the rest of this 
   
   experiment I'm going to concentrate on Warp and NT as Win95 
   
   would probably be the winner, in speed, if running just 
   
   32bit Windows apps but this is a mix. Also let me point out 
   
   that most of the applications used for these experiments 
   
   were Windows apps so these results are valid ONLY when 
   
   comparing the ability of the different OS's to run Windows 
   
   apps. I'm sure that Warp would fair much better using all 
   
   native apps but since Windows apps are so prevalent this 
   
   experiment hopefully has value for many people who like 
   
   myself own primarily Windows applications and OS/2 apps 
   
   won't run on Windows or NT for the most part. OK, same 
   
   sequence of apps, Word, database etc. Warp handled 
   
   everything fine and BTW was better than Win95 at not 
   
   letting (Service) take over the processor when it signs on, 
   
   up until the last step when I went to copy the large 
   
   directory. Everything froze. Warp did allow me to call up a 
   
   list of running (frozen) programs and exit them one at a 
   
   time, but that was all I could do other than move the 
   
   mouse. Same thing in NT but no problems at all and the 
   
   speed was much better than Warp was before it had crashed. 
   
   My theory is that NT runs Windows apps quite naturally 
   
   while Warp in order to run a Windows app in protected mode 
   
   has to load more code than does NT and the extra overhead 
   
   kills it. Before any of you Warp supporters shoot me for 
   
   reporting these results, try it yourself. Load 4 or 5 
   
   Windows apps in separate sessions and have two or more 
   
   doing something, then go to the Window's File Manger and 
   
   copy a large directory, it locks. My conclusion is this; 
   
   for best performance and good stability running a normal to 
   
   heavy amount of Windows apps go with Win95. If stability is 
   
   a major concern and you run a lot of 16 bit apps and some 
   
   OS/2 apps go with Warp and if stability is paramount and 
   
   you don't play many games go with NT if you have enough 
   
   memory. 
   
